If anything, maybe to fully appreciate Herb Alpert, one had to live
during the sixties. To many, Alpert and the TJB's music represented
something nice during a very angry and hostile era because of the Viet
Nam War. Even now when I hear Alpert, he brings back memories of
groups and people like Brazil '66 (Alpert's wife Lani Hall was one of
the vocalists), Dusty Springfield, as well as all the James Bond and
Pink Panther movies. These made life a lot more hopeful and sane
during a time when the United States was on the ropes. I wonder who
and what will represent sanity during our current era of being on the
ropes big time. It's so difficult to describe what life was like in
the sixties. One would have to live during that time to experience any
impact.

While Alpert's playing style might be lackluster in comparison to
today's trumpet players, he surely was a decent player and played
trumpet 'being himself' where he made his mark. Not familiar with the
mouthpiece he plays on (Does that really make any difference?), but he
tooted on a Benge.
