I'll bet the Brazil '66 portion of the show was better than the TJB portion.
I never saw a live performance by TJB but I did see one by Brazil '66 in
1968 and they were phenomenal.

Your story reminds me of a time when I saw a live performance by Blood,
Sweat &amp; Tears in 1970. They were playing some of their &quot;hits&quot;, but were also
playing a lot of jazz. Most of the audience was made up of teenagers who
only knew of the rock and roll side of BS&amp;T. During one song which was a
jazz tune one of the BS&amp;T members was playing an improvised solo. The
teenagers were apparently bored with it and were walking around and talking
all over the auditorium. The band stopped and one of the members got on the
microphone and told the audience that if they didn't shut up and sit down,
the band was leaving. Everybody sat down and shut up and the concert went
on. Lew Soloff even played a solo on his mouthpiece without benefit of his
trumpet attached!

